I myself re-watched the show a second time and finished it last week. Well I had the exact same experience as you had. I started noticing how poorly Walt treats Jesse and was such an asshole from the very get go. I think it has to do with the brilliant writing by Vince Gilligan and his team of writers. What they managed to do with Walt was they made us relate to him by making him an underdog. As with most people in life Walt was someone who had not lived to his full potential, someone who had been taken for granted by his family and peers alike, someone who had been always underrated. This immediately made us feel a connect to Walt. As a result, everytime Walt's ego was punctured, everytime he was insulted or considered a helpless chicken of a man by his family, friends, we felt it. We therefore turned a blind eye to the selfishness and monster pride and egocentric nature that was at the core of Walt's every bad decision. He manipulated and ill treated a naive and somewhat dim kid like Jesse and we went along with it because we had initially invested so much to the character. Only as the show went on and we realised Walt's true colors did we start to see the whole picture. So when we rewatch the show we already know Walt for who he truly is. We have lost the initial connect formed with him when watching s1 fir the first time. We know what this guy has done to Jesse and everyone around him. This is why I think Breaking Bad is the absolute pinnacle of any example for ego and pride blinding the sense of right ot wrong. We ourselves as the audience were guilty of it during our first watch.
